This paper discusses bibliometric indexes and their application in evaluating the impact of scientific research, which is relevant to several sub-categories in computer science. Specifically, the paper focuses on the PaperRank problem, which is similar to the PageRank algorithm used in web search. This suggests that the paper may belong to sub-categories related to information retrieval (cs.IR), digital libraries (cs.DL), and social networks (cs.SI). Additionally, the paper discusses the ranking of authors and journals, which could be relevant to sub-categories related to cybermetrics (cs.CY) and software engineering (cs.SD).
